**OREKA**

**Glossary of Terms**

*Complete Edition — All Three Books*

This glossary defines terms, proper nouns, and concepts specific to the Oreka campaign setting. Standard D&D 3.5e terms are not repeated here. Where a term has separate player-facing and DM-facing meanings, the DM-facing information is marked.  Pronunciation for difficult terms appears in brackets in plain-English phonetics (stressed syllables in ALL CAPS).

# **A**

**Abyssal 9, The**  The nine dark gods of Domnathar-Zhuan. They are propitiated by the Domnathar out of calculated self-preservation, not devotion. They cannot manifest on Oreka while the Lady of Fire and Tempest hold the planar door shut at the Breach. Their priests on Oreka answer prayers filtered through a barrier the gods themselves cannot cross.*  DM NOTE: The Abyssal 9 have no direct presence in Oreka. They are answering letters from a place they cannot reach. The moment the planar door opens, they do not send another army — they arrive in person.*

**Abyssal Silence**  The state of a pure Domnathar registering as complete absence on Kin-sense — not as a different species, but as nothing at all. A gap shaped like a person. Distinct from False Silence (a Deceiver cloaking ability) and from the Domnathar spell-zone effect (see: Veil of Forgetting, pending author ruling).

**Accounting, the**  The process by which a Kin spirit, upon crossing to the Summer Lands, stands before the guardians of their aligned Great Palace and accounts for their life. It is not a judgment in the mortal sense. It is a reckoning. A spirit may then be reborn or remain.

**Apotheosis***  [ah-poth-ee-OH-sis]*  The process by which a mortal Kin ascends to full godhood. Apotheosis was not possible before the Fall of Aldenheim — it is a phenomenon barely 300 years old. It requires attunement to all four elements and responds to the magnitude of an act, not the actor's moral character. Pure Domnathar cannot ascend because they have no elemental attunement.*  DM NOTE: The Domnathar apotheosis plot centers on finding a way around this constraint.*

**Ascended Gods, the**  The gods who arose through apotheosis following the Fall of Aldenheim. They are full gods mechanically — they grant spells, answer prayers, and wield divine power. They are not diminished or lesser deities. Most are human, a theological mystery discussed openly among Kin scholars. See individual deity entries.

**Assault Gate**  A Domnathar magical construct used to move large forces between worlds. The Shattering began when a misfired Assault Gate deposited an army in Oreka. A second assault gate, currently active, is the cause of the Lord of Stone's coma.*  DM NOTE: DM-only: the Lord of Stone**'**s coma is caused by the second assault gate — not the Breach, not the invasion. Even the Domnathar do not know this.*

# **B**

**Breach, the**  The dimensional wound through which the Domnathar first entered Oreka. Currently held shut from the Spirit Realm side by the Lady of Fire and Tempest. The Breach is the reason the Elemental Lords cannot fully attend to Oreka — the two most active Lords are occupied containing it.

**Breach-origin peoples**  Peoples who arrived in Oreka through the Breach from another world: goblins, wargs, hobgoblins, orcs, ogres, and kobolds. They exist outside Oreka's native elemental framework by default, but can gain elemental attunement over several generations of living in Oreka. Communities of these peoples that have been in Oreka for 300 years may already have partial attunement.

# **C**

**Cinvarin***  [SIN-vah-rin]*  The first Ascended God. Five druids who sacrificed themselves during the Fall of Aldenheim, melting the mountain to destroy the Deceiver host. They ascended as a single composite deity of unity, sacrifice, and the four elements. Neutral Good.

**Currency (Oreka)**  Oreka uses three coin denominations: the Titan (equivalent to one gold piece), the Stone (equivalent to one silver piece), and the Shard (equivalent to one copper piece). All three are properly weighted precious metal coins. Prices throughout Oreka are stated in Titans, Stones, and Shards.

# **D**

**Deceiver****'****s Feat**  A supernatural ability allowing a Kin to mask their own Kin-sense signature to read as a different race or as faint/ambiguous. It is personal use only — a Deceiver cannot mask others. It predates the Shattering. It cannot be used to produce Abyssal Silence (which is a Domnathar biological trait, not a learned ability).

**Domnathar***  [DOME-nah-thar]*  The extraplanar invaders who shattered Kin civilization 300 years ago. They have no elemental attunement and register as Abyssal Silence on Kin-sense. They cannot ascend to godhood. They are not evil by alignment in a simple sense — they are a civilization shaped by a world where only power protects. Their gods (the Abyssal 9) cannot currently reach Oreka. Lifespan up to 1,000 years; pre-invasion leaders may still be alive.*  DM NOTE: The Domnathar are not preparing another frontal assault. They are preparing to receive their gods when the Breach opens.*

**Domnathar-Zhuan***  [DOME-nah-thar ZHOO-ahn]*  The home world of the Domnathar. An underground civilization of city-states built around house rivalry as a stabilizing force, with a slave-majority population. The Abyssal 9 are propitiated, not loved. Gods of hope exist only in slave whispers.

**Dusk Guards, the**  The heavy cavalry unit of the Gilded Standard Company. Sister unit to the Gilded (medium cavalry). Both operate from the Gilded Yards.

# **E**

**Eke Concordant***  [EE-kay KON-kor-dant]*  The political institution that governed the Twelve Kingdoms before the Shattering. Seated at the Great Gap pass through the outer Giant's Teeth. Its Lord Mayor city-state structure survived the Shattering in the Shore Eruskan settlements, where every city, town, and hamlet still has a Lord Mayor.

**Elemental Affinity**  The elemental alignment possessed by every Kin from birth, determined by bloodline and race. It is innate and permanent — it does not change with class, level, or multiclassing. It provides Elemental Tolerance (Resistance 2 against the primary element's energy type) and modifies spellcasting (+1 caster level for aligned spells, -1 for opposed spells). See the four elements for associations.

**Elemental Lords, the**  The four creator-gods of Oreka: Lord of Stone (Earth), Lady of Fire, Lady Tempest / Lady of the Sea (Water), and the Youngest Brother / Lord of Wind (Air). They shaped Oreka from primordial chaos and created the Kin peoples. They are not Ascended Gods — they predate apotheosis entirely. Current status varies.*  DM NOTE: Lord of Stone: comatose (second assault gate). Lady of Fire and Tempest: holding the Breach. Lord of Wind: accidentally exiled, seeking return.*

**Elemental Tolerance**  The Resistance 2 to a primary element's energy type that all Kin possess. It is intentionally modest — a marker of elemental identity, not a combat scaling mechanic. It does not increase with level. Giants and Half-Giants possess All-Element Concord (Resistance 2 to all four energy types).

# **F**

**False Silence**  A personal supernatural ability (Su) available to Domnathar Deceivers. It is a soul-level cloak on a single Domnathar that causes them to not register on Kin-sense at all — not as a void, not as another species, simply as absent. It cannot be dispelled. It is not a zone effect. Only one Domnathar per use of False Silence is cloaked.

**Far Riders**  The Mytrone lancer component of a unified brotherhood, paired with the Wind-Riders (the Pasua mounted archer component). They are two halves of one institution, not two separate organizations. The split naming is intentional and is a source of confusion that in-world scholars discuss.

**Farborn**  Peoples who originate from a plane with different rules than Oreka's elemental framework. Unlike Kin, Farborn can produce half-breeds because their planar origin does not impose the same biological constraints. New Farborn do not register on Kin-sense. Farborn who transition into Oreka's framework can gain Kin-sense registration over generations.

# **G**

**Giant****'****s Teeth**  Two parallel mountain ranges that wrap the entire planet, sealing moisture inside the Oreka interior and creating the Infinite Desert corridor between them.

**Great Palaces, the**  Four anchor points in the Summer Lands, each a mini-elemental zone corresponding to one of the four Elemental Lords. They are self-sustaining and do not require the Lords to be present to function. The dead Kin account for their lives at the Great Palaces.

# **H**

**Hareem***  [hah-REEM]*  The Golden Rose. The only Chaotic Evil Ascended God. A bard who killed all twelve human kings one year after the Fall of Aldenheim, suffocating them with her own breath as they confessed their failures. She died in the act and ascended. Her portfolio — revenge, music, justice — is retributive under CE alignment. Worshipped by the wronged, the desperate, angry bards, and grieving parents.

**House Burath**  A Domnathar mutation house. Their specialty is giving non-Kin spirits new bodies. Recipients of these bodies are typically unaware of what was done to them.

# **I**

**Indorach***  [IN-doh-rahk]*  A Domnathar house unique in having no Abyssal 9 patron. Nihilistic and atheist by Domnathar standards. They believe in discipline, force, and their own capability. Their dead become spirits or, upon learning belief, grieve the absence of the Elemental Lords — contributing to the Sand Wraith problem in the Infinite Desert.

# **K**

**Keeper**  The title for the Emperor of Oreka. Not "Emperor" — the correct form is Keeper.

**Kharazhad***  [KAR-ah-ZHAD]*  The Rarozhki fortress-forge city in a volcanic caldera. Population approximately 20,000, over 90% dwarves. Headquarters of the Stone Covenant. Oreka's second-largest trade city. The sacred flame of Kharazhad is a pinprick shrine to the Palace of Flames. Governed by the hereditary Thaneship of House Stonefire.

**Kin**  All native races of Oreka who possess elemental attunement: the three Dwarf peoples (Visetri, Rarozhki, Pekakarlik), the four Elf peoples (Kovaka, Na'wasua, Pasua, Hasura), the five Human peoples (Orean, Eruskan, Taraf-Imro, Mytroan, and the fifth unnamed), Halflings, Giants, Half-Giants, Gnomes, and others. Kin cannot produce half-breeds because the elemental framework constrains their biology.

**Kin-sense**  The passive supernatural resonance shared by all Kin peoples. It functions as a sixth sense identifying elemental attunement type and emotional state within 60 feet (30 feet in elemental disturbance, 120 feet in deep calm). It passes through barriers up to 5 feet thick. It is not magic — it cannot be dispelled, counterspelled, or suppressed by an antimagic field. Only False Silence and related Domnathar effects can suppress it.

# **L**

**Lament of Kings**  Three simultaneous things: (1) a druidic ritual performed at the Fall of Aldenheim; (2) the blasted plain that sits above the ruins of Aldenheim, where Kin-sense is permanently unstable; (3) the poem recording the deaths of the twelve kings at Hareem's hand, in which the kings confessed their failures as they died. The poem sparked a civilization-wide return-to-roots movement that produced the Stone Covenant, the Lament festival, and rebuilt Kin alliances.

**Lord of Stone**  The Elemental Lord of Earth. One of the four creator-gods. Both "Lord of Stone" and "Lord of Earth" are valid names for this deity. Currently comatose due to the effects of a second Domnathar assault gate. The Domnathar do not know this.*  DM NOTE: DM-only: the coma is caused by a second assault gate separate from the Breach.*

# **M**

**Magi***  [MAH-jee]*  Oreka's oldest and most fundamental spellcasting tradition, predating all other casters. Magi draw directly from elemental forces. There are three Chosen Paths, including the Path of the Seer (Wisdom-based). Not to be pronounced as MAY-jy.

**Mithril Chains**  The transport chain network operating on the Kailian and Apelian seas. Staffed by Shore Eruskan crews. Shares a name with the Mithril Legion, which is an intentional in-world red herring — there is no connection between the two institutions.

**Mithril Legion**  The Visetri wandering brotherhood. A player-facing, well-known military order. One of the Three Military Orders. Their call sign and inner structure are public knowledge. Shares a name with the Mithril Chains transport network — this is a deliberate in-world red herring.

# **N**

**Na****'****wasua***  [nah-WAH-soo-ah]*  The wind-aligned elves. They maintain twenty Giant-built sky-islands: sixteen inhabited orbiters, two polar anchors, one grounded freefloater (Sundrift Veil in Tidebloom), and one erratic freefloater. Public knowledge accounts for seventeen islands; the Na'wasua conceal three.

# **P**

**Pekakarlik***  [PEH-kah-KAR-lik]*  The water-aligned dwarves. Homeland at and around Peravost, the City of Bridges. Expert river engineers and navigators.

**Peravost***  [PAIR-ah-vost]*  City of Bridges. The Pekakarlik homeland city, built where the Great River splits below Sylaraeth. A Guild City with approximately 15,000 permanent residents (80% dwarf) and 5,000-10,000 river crews at peak season. Closely allied with Sylaraeth.

# **R**

**Rarozhki***  [rah-ROZH-kee]*  The fire-aligned dwarves. Homeland at Kharazhad. Smiths, warriors, and keepers of the sacred flame.

# **S**

**Sand Wraiths**  Mal-aligned grief spirits of Kin who cross back to Oreka because the Elemental Lords are missing or silent. They are not Giant spirits. They arise from the grief of the Accounting process being incomplete — spirits who cannot fully rest because the Lords who should receive them are absent or occupied.

**Sea Falls**  The subterranean tunnel through the planet's crust connecting the Kailian Sea (north) and Apelian Sea (south). Tidal flow is seasonal, driven by Oreka's two moons. Halflings ride submersibles through it twice yearly as a traditional race and communal event. The interior is chaotic and unmapped.

**Shattering, the**  The civilization-ending event triggered by the Domnathar invasion through the misfired Assault Gate. The public-facing history records the 42-day siege of Aldenheim. The full history (100 additional days of underground war, total 142 days) is not widely known.*  DM NOTE: DM-only: the siege lasted 142 days total. The surface city fell at Day 42. Durak Stonewatch led the underground war from Day 42 to Day 142 before falling and ascending as the second apotheosis.*

**Shrines**  Pinprick openings into the Spirit Realm aimed at the relevant Great Palace zone. Maintained by whoever uses the location — a farmer tends the brook shrine, a sailor tends the harbor shrine. Shrines grow from accumulated gratitude, not doctrine. There are no permanent temple hierarchies governing them.

**Spirit Realm (Summer Lands)**  The single combined afterlife plane for all Kin. It is not divided into four separate planes. The four Great Palaces are anchor points and mini-elemental zones within it. Universal Kin term across all cultures: Summer Lands.

**Stone Covenant**  The Kin-wide standing army headquartered at Kharazhad. One of the Three Military Orders. Public knowledge confirms the Stone Covenant exists; its connection to the Mithril Legion and Steelward Host is revealed only to full members. Call signs: "We Stand for the Host" / "the stone remembers." Founded by Thane Karveth Stonefire.

**Summer Lands**  See Spirit Realm. The universal Kin term for the afterlife plane.

**Sylaraeth***  [SIL-ah-reeth]*  A rebuilt Veil city in the Twin Rivers region. Crystal spires. Attunement crystals grant minor flight, featherfall, healing factor, and sustenance within the city. Kaleidoscope colors filter through the Aetherial Veil from Spirit Realm light. The Aetherial Veil is a post-Deceivers' War defense: any Deceiver entering the city is forcefully ejected. It is a prototype with a blueprint for replication.

# **T**

**Tempest**  The canonical title for the Lady of Water (Lady of the Sea). Both "Tempest" and "Lady of the Sea" are valid. Currently active, holding the Breach alongside the Lady of Fire.

**Thalorien***  [tha-LOR-ee-en]*  An Oreka-specific term. [Author note: definition to be confirmed against current regional guide usage — appears in Canon Bible Chapter references.]

**Titan**  See Currency. A properly weighted gold coin; the highest Oreka denomination.

**Twelve Kingdoms**  The twelve pre-Shattering human kingdoms, all located in Kinsweave and northern Eternal Steppe, radiating north and south from the Great Gap. Each kingdom was approximately ten days by wagon from its neighbors. Cities include Glink and Wren (a two-city kingdom: fourteen cities, twelve kingdoms). Two to three kingdoms lay south of the pass on the Steppe side. Aldenheim lay below Highridge, south of the Scorchspires.

# **V**

**Vael****'****domin***  [VAY-el DOH-min]*  An Oreka-specific term. [Author note: definition to be confirmed.]

**Veils**  Larger, sustained overlaps between Oreka and the Spirit Realm — unlike Shrines (pinpricks), Veils are extended zones where both planes occupy the same space. The Aetherial Veil over Sylaraeth is an artificially created Veil. Domnathar are cosmologically incompatible with Veil infrastructure.

**Visetri***  [VIH-seh-tree]*  The earth-aligned dwarves. Lords of the overland trade routes. One of three dwarf peoples. The canonical spelling is Visetri — not "Vestri."

# **W**

**Wind-Riders**  The Pasua mounted archer component of a unified brotherhood, paired with the Far Riders (the Mytrone lancer component). Two halves of one institution. They initiated the Running War. The split naming is canonical and intentional.

**AUTHOR NOTES**

*Items marked [Author note: definition to be confirmed] require a ruling before the glossary is finalized. Currently flagged: Thalorien, Vael**'**domin. A ruling is also needed on the canonical name for the Domnathar spellcasting zone effect (currently referred to as **"**Veil of Forgetting**"** in the editorial gap analysis — awaiting author confirmation).*